This hinders progress toward cooperation in establishing sustainable, middle-income communities. Nashville has seen economic booms from high income transplants moving to the city from elsewhere. These transplants come and go unpredictably, with no interest in serving the community-- clogging the roads, inflating housing and retail prices, and discouraging homeownership.
